Dr. Jeffrey L. Caruso writes:
>
>>======================================================================
>>                               CFJ 937
>>
>>"No Player is currently required to report a change in Blots resulting
>> from the commission of an Infraction."
>>
>>======================================================================
>
>Decision of the Justiciar: FALSE
>
>Judge Steve reasoned that both the Herald and the player reporting the
>infraction are required by the Rules to report the change in Blots (though
>in different ways).  Either of these will make the statement FALSE, and inb
>this appeal I will concentrate on the second of these.
>
>If someone executes a Payment Order for indulgences away from a player to
>the Bank, this is a report of a new Blot (or Blots), and is implicitly a
>report of a change in Blots.  Thus the statement is FALSE if the Rules
>require any player to execute any such POs.
>
>Rule 1504 requires the player reporting an Infraction to execute a PO for
>Indulgences to apply the penalty for the Infraction.  No Rule of higher
>precedence appears to absolve em of this duty. Therefore the Statement is
>FALSE.
>
>In post-judgement discussion, Laurent made much of a supposed conflict
>between Rules 1435 and 1504. But even if these Rules imposed the
>requirement on different Players, that does not constitute a conflict. If
>Rule 1504 requires me to execute a PO and rule 1435 requires Laurent to
>execute a PO then I suppose we would both need to execute the PO's.  In any
>case at least one player would be required to execute the PO and thus
>report a change in Blots.
>
>Even if (for the sake of argument) there was a conflict, 1504's requirement
>could only be removed by a higher-precedence rule requiring a different
>player to perform the duty.  In this case there would still be a player
>required to execute the PO, with the same conclusion.
>
>However, in eir argument Laurent wants to have it both ways.  First, he
>claims that 1435 and 1504 require different players to execute the PO.
>Then he claims that 1504 does not actually require a Player to execute the
>PO.  These cannot both be true.
>
>My higher point is that the mere potential for conflict does not invalidate
>the lower-precedence Rule.  If 1504 specifies a player unequivocally, and
>1435 tries to specify a player but fails, then there is not an actual
>conflict.

Very elegant, Jeff. You manage to answer the question posed by the 
Statement without resolving who it is in fact that is required to 
report changes in Blots in various circumstances. But this more
prosaic question still interests me. I tried to answer it in my
Judgement, but as I still haven't seen Morendil' objections (although
subsequent remarks of his give good hints as to what they must be),
I can't be completely certain that I did so properly. At any rate,
I can be reasonably sure that this question hasn't yet been answered
to Morendil's satisfaction, and I'd like to achieve that if possible.

So: an open question to Scott, Jeff, Morendil and anyone else who
might care to express an opinion. Let's take a very specific case,
mentioned in my Judgement. In the case where the Infraction of
Delayed COE Response (defined in R1431) has been committed, who, if
anyone, is required to report the 'change in Blots'? Explain your
answer.

For the record, here's my answer to the above question. It's the
answer you'd intuitively expect: the Player making the COE is
required to report the change in Blots. R1431 states that:

      A Player who fails to post a Response within the alloted time
      commits the Infraction of Delayed COE Response, carrying a
      penalty of 1 Blot, to be reported by the Player who posted the
      Claim.

I note, however, (which I did not note in my Judgement) that there is
a certain ambiguity here, similar to one also found in R1504, as to
precisely what it is the Player who posted the Claim is required to
report. Is it the commission of the Infraction? Is it the commission
of the Infraction and the incursion of the penalty? Just the
incursion of the penalty? My answer falls out most straightforwardly
if we take either of the latter two views, for then the Player who
posted the Claim will be required to report the incursion of a 1 Blot
penalty, and surely even Morendil will agree that such a report
constitutes a report of a change in Blots, and so meets the condition
in R1435 as to who is to execute the Payment Orders for Indulgences
arising out of gains in Blots.

But let's be as generous to Morendil as we can be. What if we defend
the first of the possibilities described above, that R1431 requires
the Player who posted the Claim only to report the incursion of the
Infraction, and nothing more? Now Morendil's claim that R1435 does not
succeed in specifying a Player who is to report the change in Blots
looks more plausible. But that still leaves us with the by-now familiar
observation that even if R1435 doesn't specify anyone, R1504 certainly
does:

      Penalties for Infractions are applied immediately upon their
      legal report, and the Player making the report of the Infraction
      shall execute whatever Payment Order(s) are required to apply
      the penalty specified for that Infraction. 

So even if we resolved the ambiguity in R1431 in favour of the
interpretation that the Player making the Claim is required by that
Rule only to report the commission of the Infraction and nothing else,
R1504 requires that same Player to execute the necessary Payment
Orders for Indulgences, and this report, I hope Morendil will agree,
constitutes a report of a change in Blots. Therefore, it appears
that regardless of the stance one takes with respect to the ambiguity
in R1431, it is, as I claimed, the Player who posted the Claim who is
required to report a change in Blots arising from the commission of
the Infraction of Delayed COE Response.

I have tried, in the argument offerred above, to be both as clear
and explicit in my reasoning and my assumptions as I can be, and
as generous to Morendil as my respect for him warrants. I am sure
that if elements of my argument remain dissatisfactory to him, he
will soon answer with his reasons.

