On Thu, 4 Sep 1997, Scott Goehring wrote:

> But it's a close call.  Rule 101 says "the Rules then in effect".  If
> Rule 1513 stated that a body of law "has no effect" if it has not been
> made available, then there would be no conflict.  I suspect I would
> have a hard time answering the question were I asked to judge whether
> a Rule, the text of which had not been made available, was therefore a
> Rule not presently in effect by the virtues of Rule 1513.

To limit the effect of another Rule, 1513 would at the very least have to
take Precedence over it.

Rule 1513 seems to be making the very fishy assumption that Rules are not
Nomic Entities. If we don't accept this assumption we must consider
whether its Precedence Clause might put itself above some other Rules.

I consider it a general principle(*) that 1482 cannot be unseated by
low-Powered Rules (besides, 1513 doesn't try to do this in any case) and
so high-Powered Rules are above 1513. This includes 1030. 

The Precedence requirement of 1513 does seem to imply that lower-numbered
Rules take Precedence, and so 1513 cannot be construed as trying to take
Precedence over lower-numbered Rules.

This implies that 1513 will take Precedence over higher-numbered Power=1
Rules, and may manage to strip them of their ability to require Player
actions without being made available.

Greetings,
Ørjan.

