> Very elegant, Jeff. You manage to answer the question posed by the
> Statement without resolving who it is in fact that is required to
> report changes in Blots in various circumstances. But this more
> prosaic question still interests me.

So does it me - I'll have to check the record for cases of Infractions
being reported without the corresponding PO being executed at the same
time, I'm sure there must have been a few of those.

However, I too am quite satisfied with the Judgement of the Board of
Appeals now - no stone has been left unturned, which is the way
I like things to be. :)

> So: an open question to Scott, Jeff, Morendil and anyone else who
> might care to express an opinion. Let's take a very specific case,
> mentioned in my Judgement. In the case where the Infraction of
> Delayed COE Response (defined in R1431) has been committed, who, if
> anyone, is required to report the 'change in Blots'? Explain your
> answer.

By the Appellate decision, with which I agree to the extent that
elJefe's ruling on the absence of a conflict between 1504 and 1435
governs, this is the Player required, by 1504, to execute (which
implies, by Game Custom, to report) a PO in Indulgences, the act
itself constituting a change in Blots. Thus, indirectly, in this
instance, the Player who originated the COE.

> I note, however, (which I did not note in my Judgement) that there is
> a certain ambiguity here, similar to one also found in R1504, as to
> precisely what it is the Player who posted the Claim is required to
> report. Is it the commission of the Infraction? Is it the commission
> of the Infraction and the incursion of the penalty?  Just the
> incursion of the penalty? 

You did address the question in your Judgement, and claimed that it
was unclear but that either of the latter views could be taken; I
refuted this argument (and I do believe this would be confirmed by
the Courts) by pointing out that 'to be reported by' is a phrase of
art used for the purpose of satisfying the provision of 1503 stating

      Any Rule that defines an Infraction must also specify a
      Player or Players who are authorized to detect and report
      the commission of that Infraction; otherwise, the Infraction
      carries no penalty.

We need not ascribe any further legal purpose to the phrase 'to be
reported by', I think.

> I have tried, in the argument offerred above, to be both as clear
> and explicit in my reasoning and my assumptions as I can be, and
> as generous to Morendil as my respect for him warrants. I am sure
> that if elements of my argument remain dissatisfactory to him, he
> will soon answer with his reasons.

Quite - you've been more than fair. :)

1504 is obviously my downfall in this instance, but that is not
new - Michael had raised the issue a while back. I had replied then,
as I did more recently in response to Scott's raising the issue again
(_after_ delivering a summary Appelate Judgement, damn his twisted
Jurist's soul to whatever hell Jurists are consigned to), that the
language in 1435 took precedence over that in 1504 - which naturally
implied a conflict between the two Rules.

ElJefe ruled that there is no conflict. I can offer no counterargument
because there is no precedent to support either his decision or the
alternative, and thus he had every right to cut the Gordian Knot. But
this is what I take the decisive issue : whether Rule 1435, attempting
to specify a Player as being charged with a certain duty, but failing
to specify any particular Player, was in conflict with 1504, also 
charging a Player with the same duty, but successful in specifying that
Player.

I do not accept elJefe's argument that 1504 and 1435 could independently
authorize different Players to execute the same POs, however, because I
think the clause '[a PO] to be executed by whomever is required to report
the change in Blots' would indeed conflict with 1504's assignment of the
same duty to a different set of Players. However, I agree with elJefe that
my contention that the set defined by Rule 1435 is empty justifies the
view that 1504's own specification is therefore effective.



