>>have appointed" with "implicitly appoints"; you're still establishing
>>a legal fiction that the resigning Officer has appointed the Speaker
>>as successor, when e has, in fact, not.
>
>I disagree--I would say I have redefined "appointed" to mean something
>other than its normal usage.  And Agora has a long and proud
>tradition of doing that. :)

This is a subject with a long and complex tradition among scholars
of jurisprudence. Lon Fuller discusses it in his landmark 1931 book,
_Legal Fictions_, which I shall now have to reread, I suppose. Here
I'll just restrict myself to remarking that there is no reason to
assume that either all cases must be described as creating legal
fictions, or all cases must be described as cases of redefinition.
Subtly different pressures will push us in different directions
in different cases. Fuller discusses the cases of 'trover', the
doctrine in English common law that items forcibly repossessed in order
to pay debts or compensation are treated as having merely been 'found'.
Is the effect here that of creating a legal fiction to the effect
that the items in question were merely found, or is the effect that
of giving the verb 'to find' a special legal significance it doesn't
ordinarily have? The answer is not clear.

>To make an analogy, my current Location is the Rulekeepor's Office.
>In fact, I am currently (as I write this, of course) seated in
>a computer lab on the University of Wisconsin campus.  Do the
>Rules establish a legal fiction as to my location?  No, I would
>argue, they have redefined "Location" to mean something quite
>different from my actual position.  There is a similar distinction
>in my example above.  To highlight the distinction, suppose we
>had the following Rule: "A player may not send any messages to
>the PF while in a University of Wisconsin computer lab."  If the
>location rules were establishing a legal fiction as to
>my location, I would not be violating that Rule by sending
>this message.  If the location rules instead redefine "Location",
>(as I argue), then I would be violating that Rule.

I don't think this example serves you well, however. In the first
place, it might plausibly be argued that the definitions in Rules
1706-1710 have nothing to do with position, location, distance,
movement, paths, or any such things in the real world, but only with
Position, Location, Distance, Movement, Paths, and so on, which
distinction is marked by the use of capitalization. There no reason
to think that 'location' (small 'l') is being redefined here, or for
that matter that a legal fiction is being created to the effect that
your location is anywhere other than where you, Charles E. Carroll,
are physically located.

In the second place, even granting you your view that R1706 redefines
'location', giving it a special legal significance it doesn't already
have, it doesn't follow that you are violating your hypothetical Rule.
For if 'location' has been redefined, then it follows that for legal
purposes, your location is not the University of Wisconsin computing
labs, but the Origin, or whatever. So you wouldn't be violating the Rule.

